I found out where null characters are inserted.

In CodeReader.load() method, unintentional null characters are inserted during reading file stream and decoding to character array.

CodeReader.load() line 102.
===============================
		CharBuffer charBuffer = Charset.forName(encoding).decode(byteBuffer);
		if (charBuffer.hasArray())
			return charBuffer.array();
		// Got to copy it out
		char[] buff = new char[charBuffer.length()];
		charBuffer.get(buff);
		return buff;
===============================

In order to aviod this problem, I modified it like following,

===============================
		CharBuffer charBuffer = Charset.forName(encoding).decode(byteBuffer);
		//if (charBuffer.hasArray())
		//	return charBuffer.array();
		// Got to copy it out
		char[] buff = new char[charBuffer.length()];
		charBuffer.get(buff,0,charBuffer.length());
		return buff;
===============================

and I checked SCANNER_BAD_CHARACTER problem caused by null char didn't occur in BaseScanner.fetchToken() method after this modification.

My solution is proper? please check.

regards,

BuildManager#basicBuildLoop(IProject[] ordered, IProject[] unordered, int trigger, MultiStatus status, IProgressMonitor monitor)

calls the following api.
  basicBuild(ordered[i], trigger, status, Policy.subMonitorFor(monitor, projectWork));

so that inside of it, the passed IProgressMonitor#done is expected to be called.
However, BuildManager#basicBuildLoop(IProject[] ordered, IProject[] unordered, int trigger, MultiStatus status, IProgressMonitor monitor) has the following snippet.

	if (!project.isAccessible())
		return;
	final ICommand[] commands = ((Project) project).internalGetDescription().getBuildSpec(false);
	if (commands.length == 0)
		return;

and if these "if"s are true, no IProgressMonitor#done is called so that
the progress monitor doesn't show the correct progress. IProgressMonitor#done needs to be called there.


